## Discussion

Community-based trials can provide information about the treatment of common conditions that is not readily available from conventional controlled clinical trials.1,2,3,4 This study with the {{ drug.molecular_formula }} {{ drug.name }} was carried out by several hundred practitioners, most of whom were participating in their first research project. In some ways they were a self-selected group, for they responded to an unsolicited invitation to participate in the study and were willing to undertake the process of institutional review board approval and to make the commitment of identifying patients who could meet the study's entry criteria. In addition, they were required to follow the rules of the research plan and to accurately complete the case report forms. This type of study helps obtain data on how clinical practitioners evaluate and manage patients and how they identify and report potential adverse events. This provides different information about the overall treatment of hypertension than is obtained from clinical trials designed primarily to evaluate the efficacy and other pharmacologic characteristics of a particular drug.

The average reduction in {{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }} produced by {{ drug.name }} in this study was greater than that observed in a recent large controlled clinical trial using similar doses of this agent.8 The likely explanation for the greater effect in the present study is that observations were taken at whatever time patients happened to be seen at the physicians’ offices, often just a few hours after the drug was taken. Therefore, unlike formal trials in which drug efficacy is evaluated at trough (at the end of the dosing interval), this study measured treatment effects closer to the time of the drug's peak action. Because only a small handful of clinicians are likely to instruct their patients to withhold their therapy on the morning of an office visit, the findings in this study more clearly reflect the BPs that guide treatment decisions by doctors in practice.

A further observation of this study was the difference between the two dosage groups: those patients who responded well and remained at the starting dose of {{ drug.name }} of {{ drug.strength }} throughout the study, and those who were titrated to the 80-mg dose. In this latter group, the initial effect response to the 40-mg dose was 7.3/4.5 mm Hg, but there was an additional reduction of 7.7/5.5 mm Hg when the dose was doubled. This indicates that a meaningful number of hypertensive patients benefit substantially when treated with a higher dose. This type of information is not forthcoming from traditional parallel group studies of drug dose effects. For example, a recent large-scale controlled study of this type using {{ drug.name }} found an average difference between the 40-mg and 80-mg doses of 3.2/0.8 mm Hg,8clearly less than the decrement produced in the present study when the dose was increased from 40 to {{ drug.strength }}. This finding suggests that the shallow dose response relationships generally attributed to the {{ drug.molecular_formula }},6,10,11 may be an artifact produced by including both treatment responders and nonresponders within each dose group in the conventional studies. This does not reflect clinical practice.

Surveys of hypertension management in the United States such as the National Health and Nutrition Examination Survey ({{ drug.molecular_formula }})12 have shown that only about half of treated hypertensive patients have their {{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }} controlled (<140/90 mm Hg). One of the explanations for this disappointing finding is the apparent reluctance of clinicians—even in settings where access to care and drugs is inexpensive or completely free—to make the necessary treatment adjustments to achieve control.13In the present study, despite the clearly stated requirements of the protocol, a relatively large number of patients, particularly those aged 65 years or older, remained on the lower dose despite not being controlled. Possible explanations could include a lack of belief by practitioners in the treatment goals that have been established by guidelines committees,9 a fear of excessive {{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }} reductions or other adverse events. In future trials of this type it would be valuable to give physicians opportunities to indicate why they sometimes choose not to intensify treatment in patients not reaching {{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }} goals.

A surprising observation in this study was that 72% of the patients enrolled were not receiving antihypertensive therapy before the study. It seems unlikely that such a large number of hypertensive patients—with an average untreated {{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }} of 153/95 mm Hg—would have been diagnosed by chance at the start of this trial. Rather, it suggests that many physicians were already following patients with hypertension and were prompted by this study to initiate therapy. It also confirms the NHANES12data suggesting that, at any given time, there is a relatively large pool of diagnosed but untreated hypertensive patients in the community.

In patients whose {{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }} were previously uncontrolled, switching to the {{ drug.molecular_formula }} {{ drug.name }} significantly reduced {{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }} regardless of the drug classes that were replaced. Because this study only allowed patients to enter if their previous treatment was with monotherapy, this allowed comparison of the effects of {{ drug.name }} with other types of single agents. Not surprisingly, the best results were seen in patients previously treated with diuretics; according to the well-established vasoconstriction/volume concept of hypertension14 it would be expected that patients failing to be controlled by a diuretic would respond well to an antirenin drug such as {{ drug.name }}. Also, heterogeneous responses to differing drug classes may depend on genotype.15

It is more difficult to explain why the substitution of {{ drug.name }} in patients previously treated with angiotensin converting enzyme inhibitors or even other {{ drug.molecular_formula }} produced such good responses. There are at least four possibilities: first, a regression to the mean (placebo effect) in patients being selected for a hypertension trial; second, that {{ drug.name }} may have greater efficacy than some other antihypertensive agents,16 although a study such as this cannot be used to compare efficacies among {{ drug.molecular_formula }} or other drug classes; third, that the present protocol optimized the effects of {{ drug.name }} by encouraging use of its maximum dose; and fourth, that participation in a formal clinical trial—including the signing of an informed consent and the need for relatively frequent structured visits to the doctor—engendered a greater commitment to treatment in patients who previously might have been less compliant.

Another benefit of large-scale community-based trials is that they provide sufficient statistical power to carry out group analysis of data. When patients who were 65 years or older were compared with those who were <65 years, the effects of {{ drug.name }} on {{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }} were similar, although there was a tendency for the younger group to have a slightly greater systolic {{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }} response. This could be partly explained by a greater reluctance by physicians to undertake uptitration of the {{ drug.name }} dose in older patients with uncontrolled {{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }}. This finding suggests a further educational opportunity, for not only do older patients generally have excellent tolerance for agents such as the angiotensin receptor blockers, but they get particularly good protection against major clinical events when systolic {{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }} are adequately controlled.17,18 There were no meaningful differences between results in men and women.

Consistant with previously published data,19 the {{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }} responses in African American patients were slightly less than in whites. Increasing the {{ drug.name }} dose from 40 to {{ drug.strength }} in African American patients, however, who did not respond to the lower dose produced a sharp increase in response rate. It may be important to recognize that the best {{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }} outcomes in African American patients will generally require the use of higher doses, and this should be anticipated when undertaking their treatment.

In summary, this community study has demonstrated a {{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }} control (<140/90 mm Hg) rate of 56% for {{ drug.name }} monotherapy. Factors contributing to this high control rate included the fact that clinicians tend to measure {{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }} close to the time of peak drug effect rather than at trough as in formal clinical trials. These results also suggest that frequent office visits and participation in a structured program of treatment will enhance {{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }} control. Despite the requirements of the protocol, physicians did not always titrate drug doses in patients whose {{ drug.pharmacopoeia_standard }} were not controlled, particularly the elderly. Even so, this practice-based trial has documented that increasing the dose of the efficacious {{ drug.molecular_formula }} {{ drug.name }} from 40 to {{ drug.strength }} produced a substantial additional antihypertensive effect in noncontrolled patients, far greater than would be predicted from the modest differences between 40- and 80-mg doses observed in controlled parallel group trials. Studies such as this expand our knowledge of how an antihypertensive agent such as {{ drug.name }} can be used most effectively in clinical practice.
